English language learning among adult migrants in the UK. Whilst citizenship learning is inherent in English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL), the book argues that top-down approaches and externally-designed curricula are not a productive or useful approach. Meaningful citizenship education in adult ESOL is possible, however, if it brings social and political content centre-stage alongside pedagogy which develops the capabilities for active, grassroots, participatory citizenship. The chapters deliver a detailed examination of citizenship and ESOL in the UK. They address a range of community and college-based settings and the needs and circumstances of different groups of ESOL students, including refugees, migrant mothers, job seekers and students with mental health needs. The book draws attention to the crucial role of ESOL teachers as ‘brokers of citizenship’ mediating between national policy and the experiences and needs of adult migrant students. The book links together language pedagogy and citizenship theory with the practical concerns of ESOL teachers and students.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAdult educationzGreat Britain. 0aAdult education-Great Britain. 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingzGreat Britain. 0aCitizenship-Study and teaching-Great Britain. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 0aEnglish language-Study and teaching-Foreign speakers. 0aImmigrantsxEducationzGreat Britain. 0aImmigrants-Education-Great Britain. 0aLanguage and culturezGreat Britain. 0aLanguage and culture-Great Britain. 0aLanguage policyzGreat Britain. 0aLanguage policy-Great Britain. 0aSocial integrationxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aSocial integration-Government policy-Great Britain. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aESOL.  aEnglish teachi